abstracts.cdata!:
This is the Implementation Completion
            Report (ICR) for the Fisheries Support Services Project in
            Indonesia. The project's main objective was to increase
            non-oil exports by providing support services for private
            investments in the fisheries sector, while reducing
            government subsidies. Bank performance has been deficient in
            project identification, preparation assistance and
            appraisal, but has been generally satisfactory in
            supervision. Borrower's performance in preparing the
            project has also been deficient and performance was
            satisfactory. The key lessons learned were as follows: a)
            thorough project preparation is a prerequisite for
            successful implementation; b) project agencies tend to work
            closer together at lower levels of government; c) when
            retaining private parties in a project, a suitable selection
            procedure which takes into account competence and experience
            should be followed; d) government should impress on shrimp
            farmers not to intensify to make quick gains; e) land
            titling under the national program should be accelerated;
            and f) in terms of poverty alleviation the project would
            have achieved more if its activities had focused more on
            South East Sulawesi rather than South Sulawesi.
